    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT89-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">1. talaimakaṉ ciṟaippuṟattāṉākat tōḻi taṉṉuḷḷē colluvāḷāyc colliyatu. 2. talaimakaṟkup (C1+3+4: talaimakaṭkup) pāṅkāyiṉār kēṭpac colliya vāyiṉ maṟuttatūumām. (EA: ciṟaippuṟam.)</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. Uttered as if to herself by the confidante, while HE is behind the hedge. 2. Mediation/the door refused [and] uttered to be heard by those close to HIM.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT89">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                pāvaṭi yurala pakuvāy vaḷḷai</l>
<l>                yētiṉ mākka ṇuvaṟalu nuvalpa</l>
<l>                vaḻiva tevaṉkolip pētai yūrkkē</l>
<l>                perumpūṭ poṟaiyaṉ pēemutir kollik</l>
<l>                karuṅkaṭ ṭeyvaṅ kuṭavarai yeḻutiya</l>
<l>                nalliyaṟ pāvai yaṉṉavim</l>
<l>                melliyaṟ kuṟumakaḷ pāṭiṉaḷ kuṟiṉē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <l>Let other people do the talk</l>
                <l rend="indent">about the Vaḷḷai<note place="foot">The <term xml:lang="ta">vaḷḷai</term> seems to be a traditional song sung by women when working with grain. When we take the syntactical marks in this poem seriously, we have to construe it as the indirect object of <term xml:lang="ta">nuvaṟal</term>, that is, people talk about the way SHE sings the <term xml:lang="ta">Vaḷḷai</term>, which probably insinuates that she is not singing about dead warriors as the other women, but about her lover.</note>, [sounding] at the split mouth</l>
                <l rend="indent4">of the broad-based mortar.</l>
                <l>What harm is it to this foolish village?</l>
                <l>This tender-natured little woman was singing when pounding,<note place="foot">So SHE sang while working and was in good spirits, though people are talking.</note></l>
                <l rend="indent">like a good-natured image<note place="foot">This image of the deity on mount <term xml:lang="ta">Kolli</term> seems to be a topos. Besides KT 100, compare, for example, Kali 56.</note></l>
                <l rend="indent">of the black-eyed god drawn on the western [side of] the mountain,</l>
                <l rend="indent">the dreadful Kolli of Poṟaiyaṉ with big ornaments.</l>
                
                <lg type="alternate" resp="#Srin" sameAs="1+6b">
                  
                  <l>“If [the women] were to pound [grain], the kuṟumakaḷ would sing</l>
                  <l>[inserting the name of her lover into] the vaḷḷai [at/around] the split</l>
                  <l> mouth characteristic of the mortar with broad base”</l>
                  <l>– thus will other people talk, and emphatically at that (nuvaṟalum).</l>
                </lg>
              

                </lg>
        </div>
